{{Infobox building | name = Chinatown Fair Family Fun Center | image = Chinatown Fair storefront.jpg | image_alt = | image_caption = | former_names = Chinatown Fair | alternate_names = | status = | building_type = [[Video arcade]] | address = 8 Mott St, New York, NY 10038 | coordinates = {{coord|40.714009|-73.998511|display=inline}} | location_town = [[Chinatown, Manhattan]], [[New York City]] | location_country = United States | opened_date = 1944 | relocated_date = | website = {{URL|http://www.chinatownfair.biz/}} }}
'''Chinatown Fair Family Fun Center''' is a [[video arcade]] center located on [[Mott Street]] in [[Chinatown, Manhattan]]. Historically, the arcade catered toward competitive [[fighting game]]s. The original arcade opened in 1944 and closed in February 2011, but reopened in May 2012 under different management. Chinatown Fair has been widely regarded as [[New York City]]'s "last great arcade".<ref name="moth_TheO">{{Cite web| title = The Odd History And Uncertain Future Of Chinatown Fair, NYC's Last Great Arcade| author = Kopfstein, Janus| work = Vice Motherboard| date = 2011-02-23| accessdate = 2016-07-26| url = https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/9aaq37/the-future-of-nyc-s-most-famous-arcade}}</ref><ref name="nyti_ChinG">{{Cite web| title = Chinatown Fair’s Closing Leaves Gamers Bereft| author = Kaminer, Ariel| work = The New York Times| date = 2011-03-11| accessdate = 2016-07-26| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/13/nyregion/13critic.html}}</ref><ref name="ny.c_Manh">{{Cite web| title = Manhattan's Last Coin-Operated Arcade Memorialized In New Documentary| last = Rosenberg | first = Zoe| work = [[Curbed]] | date = 2015-11-13| accessdate = 2016-07-26| url = http://ny.curbed.com/2015/11/13/9900706/manhattans-last-coin-operated-arcade-memorialized-in-new-documentary}}</ref> == History == Chinatown Fair opened in 1944, taking over the first floor of the popular Port Arthur Chinese Restaurant building located at 7-9 Mott Street in New York City; previously, the first floor had been occupied by Soy Kee & Co., exporters, as well as the Eastern Trading Company.<ref name="VoicesOfNY">{{Cite web| title = A Stretch of Mott Street, Remembered| author = Lin, Jing| work = Voices of NY| date = 2014-09-08| accessdate = 2016-08-06| url = https://voicesofny.org/2014/09/stretch-mott-street-remembered/}}</ref><ref name="ChinaRhyming">{{Cite web| title = The Port Arthur Restaurant, Mott Street, New York City| author = French, Paul| work = China Rhyming| date = 2012-11-20| accessdate = 2016-08-06| url = http://www.chinarhyming.com/2012/11/20/the-port-arthur-restaurant-mott-street-new-york-city/}}</ref> Chinatown Fair operated as a penny arcade and small museum for many years, before becoming a video game arcade in the 1970s.<ref name="Bedford">{{Cite web| title = Cut Class and Catch This Documentary About Chinatown Fair Arcade| author = Maurer, Daniel| work = Bedford and Bowery| date = 2015-11-18| accessdate = 2016-08-06| url = http://bedfordandbowery.com/2015/11/cut-class-and-catch-this-documentary-about-chinatown-fair-arcade/}}</ref> [[Indian people|Indian]] immigrant Sam Palmer purchased the business in 1982 after having a "religious vision".<ref name="goth_Vide">{{Cite web| title = Video: Revisit The Old Days Of Chinatown Fair In This New Documentary| author = Carlson, Jen| work = Gothamist| date = 2015-11-13| accessdate = 2016-07-26| url = http://gothamist.com/2015/11/13/chinatown_fair.php| deadurl = yes| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160601002535/http://gothamist.com/2015/11/13/chinatown_fair.php| archivedate = 2016-06-01| df = }}</ref>
One of its first attractions was a dancing chicken. The dancing chicken was later replaced with a [[tic-tac-toe]] playing chicken, which was retired in the early 2000s.<ref name="nyti_Chin">{{Cite web| title = Chinatown Fair Returns, but Without Chicken Playing Tick-Tack-Toe| last = Gregory | first = Kia| work = The New York Times| date = 10 June 2012| accessdate = 2016-07-26| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/11/nyregion/chinatown-fair-returns-but-without-chicken-playing-tick-tack-toe.html?_r=0}}</ref> In the 1970s and 1980s, the arcade hosted many retro generation games including ''[[Pac-Man]]'' and ''[[Space Invaders]]''. In 1991, after the release of ''[[Street Fighter II: The World Warrior]]'', Chinatown Fair switched focus to competitive fighting games. By the late 1990s ''Street Fighter'', ''[[Marvel vs. Capcom]]'', ''[[The King of Fighters]]'', ''[[Soulcalibur (video game)|Soulcalibur]]'', ''[[Tekken]]'' and other fighting games were commonly played. Top players such as [[Justin Wong]], [[NYChrisG]], Michael "Yipes" Mendoza, and Sanford Kelly frequented the establishment.<ref name="nyti_AnAr">{{Cite web| title = An Arcade Offers Face-to-Face Fighting in the Age of Online Gaming| last = Chibber | first = Kabir| work = The New York Times| date = 4 August 2010| accessdate = 2016-07-26| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/05/fashion/05Chinatown.html}}</ref>
As of 2010, ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that Chinatown Fair was among the last video arcades in the city. Video arcades have been in decline with the rise of home video games. The newspaper reported that it became "a center for all the outcasts in the city to bond over their shared love" of classic arcade and fighting video games no longer popular in modern arcades, with titles including the original ''[[Street Fighter 2]]'' (1991), ''[[King of Fighters]]'' (1996), and ''[[Ms. Pac-Man]]''. Other groups congregated around ''[[Dance Dance Revolution]]'' machines and racing games. Unlike the norm at other arcades, where winning players continue until deposed, Chinatown Fair players play a maximum of three or four continuous games.<ref name="nyti_AnAr"/>{{better source|reason=Was this the intended meaning from the interviewee?|date=June 2017}}
In February 2011, Chinatown Fair closed down. On May 5, 2012 over a year later it reopened under a new name "Chinatown Fair Family Fun Center" with new manager and part owner, Lonnie Sobel.<ref name="goth_Vide"/> Former competitive players criticized the new arcade for catering toward casual players, with the new ownership explaining that they were targeting a new clientele.<ref name="thev_NewY">{{Cite web| title = New York's Chinatown Fair arcade reopens, but the game has changed| last = Kopfstein | first = Janus | work = The Verge| date = 2012-05-07| accessdate = 2016-07-26| url = https://www.theverge.com/2012/5/7/3004259/chinatown-fair-arcade-grand-re-opening}}</ref> Competitive fighting game players relocated to [[Next Level (arcade)|Next Level]], a [[Brooklyn]] arcade, which opened in 2011.<ref name="goth_Chin">{{Cite web| title = Chinatown Fair Resurfaces in Brooklyn As Next Level Arcade| author = Jaya Saxena| work = Gothamist| date = 2011-03-07| accessdate = 2016-07-27| url = http://gothamist.com/2011/03/07/chinatown_fair_resurfaces_as_next_l.php| deadurl = yes| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160520071123/http://gothamist.com/2011/03/07/chinatown_fair_resurfaces_as_next_l.php| archivedate = 2016-05-20| df = }}</ref>
The arcade is the focus of the 2015 documentary, ''[[The Lost Arcade]]'', which was released in [[New York City]] on August 12, 2016.<ref name="city_When">{{Cite web| title = When Video Game Arcades Were Community Centers| author = Jessica Leigh Hester| work = CityLab| date = 2016-07-21| accessdate = 2016-07-26| url = http://www.citylab.com/navigator/2016/07/video-game-arcade-chinatown-fair-documentary/492059/}}</ref>
