{{Infobox film | name = Panggilan Darah | image = De Orient Magazine advertisement for Panggilan Darah (1941).jpg{{!}}border | image_size = 300 | border = | alt = A black-and-white advertisement | caption = Magazine advertisement, ''De Orient'' | director = [[Sutan Usman Karim]] | producer = [[Tjho Seng Han]] | screenplay = Sutan Usman Karim | narrator = | starring ={{plain list| *[[Dhalia]] *[[Soerip]] }} | music = | cinematography = | editing = | studio = [[Oriental Film]] | distributor = | released = {{Film date|df=yes|1941|06|30|Dutch East Indies}} | runtime = | country = [[Dutch East Indies]] | language = Indonesian | budget = | gross = }}
'''''Panggilan Darah''''' (Indonesian for ''Call of Blood'') is a 1941 film from the [[Dutch East Indies]] (now [[Cinema of Indonesia#History|Indonesia]]) written and directed by [[Sutan Usman Karim]] and produced by [[Tjho Seng Han]] for [[Oriental Film]]. The [[black and white|black-and-white]] film starred [[Dhalia]] and [[Soerip]] as orphaned sisters trying to make a living in the colonial capital of [[Batavia, Dutch East Indies|Batavia]] (now [[Jakarta]]) before moving to [[Kudus, Kudus|Kudus]] to work at a [[kretek|clove cigarette]] factory.
Shot on location at an orphanage and two factories in [[central Java]], ''Panggilan Darah'' was a modest commercial success in the Indies and [[Singapore]]. Its soundtrack, which featured nine ''[[kroncong]]'' songs, received popular acclaim, and the film's acting received critical praise. Despite this success, Oriental was unable to recoup its expenses, and merged into Multi Film soon afterwards. ''Panggilan Darah'', which was screened as late as 1952, may now be [[lost film|lost]].
==Plot== Orphaned sisters Dhalia and Soerip (themselves) leave their village in an attempt to make a living in the colonial capital of Batavia (now [[Jakarta]]). After a long period of misery, they are accepted as housemaids at the home of [[Hajji]] Iskak (Mochtar Widjaja). Although initially elated, they find that Iskak's wife (Wolly Sutinah) is a cruel mistress who often beats them. Meanwhile, Iskak's would-be son-in-law is constantly flirting with Dhalia, much to his fiancée's dismay.
The sisters decide to run away from Iskak's home. They make their way to [[Kudus, Kudus|Kudus]] and find work at the Nitisemito [[kretek|clove cigarette]] factory with the help of their friend ([[S. Poniman]]). Not long after their escape, Iskak receives a guest who reveals that the two were his nieces. This revelation spurs Iskak to take out advertisements in newspapers, looking for the young women and asking them to return to Batavia.
Iskak's search has little success until the sisters receive news that he is looking for them, and they quickly return to Batavia. There, the sisters are greeted with open arms. Iskak's wife regrets her earlier treatment of the girls and repents, treating them splendidly and supporting Dhalia's plans to open an orphanage.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=269}}
==Production== ''Panggilan Darah'' was the [[film director|directorial]] debut of [[Sutan Usman Karim]], commonly known as Suska, a journalist and former member of the touring theatrical group Bolero under [[Andjar Asmara]]. With ''Panggilan Darah'', which he also wrote, Suska became one of several reporters who entered the film industry in the 1940s.{{efn|Others included Andjar Asmara and [[Inoe Perbatasari]] {{harv|Biran|2009|pp=216, 262}}.}}<ref>{{harvnb|Biran|2009|pp=216, 262}}; {{harvnb|''Pertjatoeran Doenia'' 1941a, Warta dari Studio|p=18}}.</ref> He directed the film for the Batavia-based film company [[Oriental Film|Oriental]], run by the [[Chinese Indonesians|ethnic Chinese]] producer Tjho Seng Han. The production house had previously released three films, all directed by [[Njoo Cheong Seng]], but after Njoo departed for [[Fred Young (director)|Fred Young]]'s Majestic, Oriental had required a new director.<ref>{{harvnb|Biran|2009|p=229}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Kredit Panggilan Darah}}.</ref>
The film was shot in [[black and white]] by the [[Indo people|Indo]] cameraman J. J. W. Steffens, with editing handled by Soemardjan.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Kredit Panggilan Darah}} Scenes were shot at an orphanage for Muslims owned by S. Z. Gunawan (who played herself in the film), as well as at the Nitisemito cigarette factory in Kudus and at a [[batik]] factory in [[Pekalongan]] owned by Tan Jauw Lin.{{sfn|''Pertjatoeran Doenia'' 1941a, Warta dari Studio|p=18}} Writing in 2009, the Indonesian film historian [[Misbach Yusa Biran]] suggested that the film may have been partly sponsored by Nitisemito&mdash;one of the largest cigarette factories in the Indies in the 1940s&mdash;based on the factory's prominence in the plot.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=270}}
Dhalia, Soerip, and S.&nbsp;Poniman, already known for their singing prowess, starred in ''Panggilan Darah'', which featured nine ''[[kroncong]]'' songs.{{efn|''[[Kroncong]]'' is a type of traditional music with Portuguese influences which was highly popular with the lower-class [[Native Indonesians|indigene]] of the time {{harv|Biran|1982|p=11}}.}}<ref>{{harvnb|Biran|2009|p=270}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Panggilan Darah}}.</ref> Additional roles were taken by Wolly Sutinah and Mochtar Widjaja. The film marked Sutinah's debut for the company; the other cast members had previous screen credits with Oriental.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Filmografi Dhalia}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Filmografi Soerip}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Filmografi S Poniman}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Filmografi Mochtar Widjaja}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Filmografi Wolly Sutinah}}.</ref>
==Release and reception== [[File:Miss Soerip, 1941.jpg|thumb|upright|Promotional image of [[Soerip]] released for the film]] ''Panggilan Darah'' debuted at the Orion Theatre in Batavia on 30 June 1941. It was reported as a modest success,<ref>{{harvnb|Biran|2009|p=229}}; {{harvnb|''Pertjatoeran Doenia'' 1941b, Warta dari Studio|p=28}}.</ref> making most of its money from lower class audiences.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=270}} It was screened in [[Surabaya]], East Java, by August,{{sfn|''Soerabaijasch Handelsblad'' 1941, Film Sampoerna theater}} and by September it had been shown in [[Singapore]], then part of [[British Malaya]].{{sfn|''The Straits Times'' 1941, (untitled)}} A [[novelization|novelisation]] by [[Roestam Sutan Palindih]] was published by the [[Yogyakarta]]-based Kolff-Buning Publishers that year.{{sfn|WorldCat, Panggilan Darah}}
Reviews of ''Panggilan Darah'' were mixed to positive. The journalist Soerono,{{efn|Soerono was, at the time he wrote the article, the editor of the weekly ''Adil'' and the monthly ''Alfatch'' {{harv|Soerono|1941|p=18}}.}} writing in the entertainment magazine ''Pertjatoeran Doenia dan Film'', was pleased with the film's depiction of the [[Islam and children#Orphaned children|Islamic mandate]] to take care of orphans.{{sfn|Soerono|1941|p=18}} An anonymous review in the Surabaya-based daily ''[[Soerabaijasch Handelsblad]]'' found the film "something special"{{efn|Original: "is iets bijzonders".}} and praised Soerip's spontaneity in her role.{{sfn|''Soerabaijasch Handelsblad'' 1941, Film Sampoerna theater}} Biran wrote that lower-class audiences enjoyed the film's music, while the [[intelligentsia]] scoffed at the idea that a factory supervisor would bring a guitar to work.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=270}} He found the plot illogical, asking why the sisters would not have worked in their own home village and how the destitute sisters could have made the journey from Batavia to Kudus, over {{convert|400|km}} away.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=270}}
==Legacy== Unable to recoup its expenses, Oriental later merged into the Dutch-owned Multi Film and ceased producing works of fiction.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=229}} Suska left the company and joined [[The Teng Chun]]'s Java Industrial Film, for which he directed ''[[Ratna Moetoe Manikam]]''.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=216}} Most of the cast remained active in cinema for the remainder of their lives. Both Dhalia and Soerip remained in the film industry for the next fifty years; they acted in their last feature films, ''[[Pendekar Jagad Kelana]]'' (''Warrior of Jagad Kelana'') and ''[[Sejak Cinta Diciptakan]]'' (''Since Love was Created'') respectively, in 1990.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Filmografi Dhalia}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Filmografi Soerip}}.</ref> Poniman and Sutinah would remain active in the industry until 1975 and 1986.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Filmografi S Poniman}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Filmografi Wolly Sutinah}}.</ref> Only Widjaja is not recorded as performing in any more films.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Filmografi Mochtar Widjaja}}
''Panggilan Darah'' was screened as late as August 1952,{{sfn|''Algemeen Indisch Dagblad'' 1952, Cinemas}} but may now be [[lost film|lost]]. Movies in the Indies were recorded on highly flammable [[nitrate film]], and after a fire destroyed much of [[Produksi Film Negara]]'s warehouse in 1952, old films shot on nitrate were deliberately destroyed.{{sfn|Biran|2012|p=291}} The American visual anthropologist [[Karl G. Heider]] writes that all Indonesian films from before 1950 are lost.{{sfn|Heider|1991|p=14}} However, J. B. Kristanto's ''[[Katalog Film Indonesia]]'' (''Indonesian Film Catalogue'') records several as having survived at [[Sinematek Indonesia]]'s archives, and Biran writes that several Japanese propaganda films have survived at the [[Netherlands Government Information Service]].{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=351}}
